On Jun 6, 2004, at 9:53 PM, Curt Sampson wrote:

&gt; It seems to me little effort at all to create an appropriate
&gt; MockBigObject, if you set up your system right. Let&#39;s say your
&gt; doSomething looks like this:
&gt;
&gt;     public void doSomething(BigObject biggie) {
&gt; 	String s = biggie.getStringValue();
&gt; 	int i = biggie.getIntValue();
&gt; 	if (s == null && i == 0)
&gt; 	    biggie.setResult(true);
&gt; 	else
&gt; 	    biggie.setResult(false);
&gt;     }
&gt;
&gt; Test it with:
&gt;
&gt;     BigObject mock = new BigObject() {
&gt; 	public String getStringValue() {
&gt; 	    return null;
&gt; 	}
&gt; 	public int getIntValue() {
&gt; 	    return 0;
&gt; 	}
&gt; 	public void setResult(boolean result) {
&gt; 	    assertTrue(result);
&gt; 	}
&gt;     }
&gt;     objectUnderTest.doSomething(mock);

Yes, I agree that this can be a powerful and effective mocking 
technique.

Sometimes I find it&#39;s just too easy to create a mock.  I want to first 
answer the question: &quot;Does this method need to take BigObject as a 
parameter?&quot;  If the answer is yes, then answer: &quot;How do I mock 
BigObject?&quot;  I have to force myself to ask the first question; the 
second question seems to want to be the first question.

&gt; The secret to mocking, IMHO, is to make mocks that do the bare minimum
&gt; necessary to test the functionality in question, rather than trying to
&gt; make ones that actually look or act anything like the real object.

Great point!

Mike
